1.) Introduction

Sports forecasting is a very common and important issue recently since there are several people interested in sports competitions. More than that, some people are sports fanatic. Therefore, people are curious about the match results and there are some companies determining the odds for corresponding games and people can bet on sport competitions. These companies (i.e.Bookmakers) consider the properties of teams and other parameters, then they determine the odds for corresponding matches. This project was carried out for examining the effectiveness of different bookmakers about determining different types of odds. During this project, the data of England Premier League was used to analyze the bookmakers behaviors.

2.) Task 1

2.1.) Task 1.a

In this part, 5 of bookmakers were selected for analyzing their behaviors about determining over odds. The implied probabilities and the fractions were calculated for both initial and final over odds for each bookmaker. For a successful performance, it is expected that the points are around y=x lines.

Figure 1: Fraction vs implied values for initial over odds of Pinnacle

Figure 2: Fraction vs implied values for final over odds of Pinnacle

As it can be seen from the Figure 1 and 2, the given probabilities for the over seems to be correct in general since the fraction and implied probability values are around y=x line. There are some exceptional points which are strictly far away from y=x line. For these points, it can be said that there is not enough data (matches and given odds by the bookmaker); therefore, these points can be ignored. Moreover, it can be obtained that the final odds for over of Pinnacle are more accurate than the starting odds because the points of final odds are more close to y=x line. In other words, Pinnacle changes its probabilities according to some circumstances and it makes better the predictions. For its starting odds, Pinnacle is more successful between the fractions 0.4 and 0.7 in general. For final odds, it predicts well for the fractions between 0.2 and 0.7.

Figure 3: Fraction vs implied values for initial over odds of BetVictor

Figure 4 : Fraction vs implied values for final over odds of BetVictor

In general, BetVictor can predict whether the matches will finish as over since the points are around y=x line in general. For the starting odds, BetVictor is slightly more effective around the fraction values 0.4 and 0.55 while for the final odds, it is more successful about prediction around the fraction values 0.4 and 0.65. Moreover, it can be said that after changing its odds (from starting odd to final odd), it can predict match result (over or not) more accurately since the points in figure 4 are more close to y=x line.

Figure 5 : Fraction vs implied values for initial over odds of Betsson

Figure 6 : Fraction vs implied values for final over odds of Betsson

This can be obtained from figure 4 and 6 that Betsson can predict whether the match will finish with over because the point are around y=x line in general. Of course there are some exceptional points because of insufficient data. It is not possible that Betsson can predict all matches correctly but some points are strictly far away from y=x line, they are exceptional points and can be ignored. This can be said that after changing its starting odds to final odds, Betssons predictions become better as it can be seen from the figures since the points in figure 6 are closer to y=x line than the points in figure 5.

Figure 7 : Fraction vs implied values for initial over odds of Betway

Figure 8 : Fraction vs implied values for final over odds of Betway

For the bookmaker Betway, the starting odds are more accurate around the fraction 0.4 and 0.65. On the other hand, its predictions become better after changing its odds (final odds) around the fraction values between 0.4 and 0.75.

Figure 9 : Fraction vs implied values for initial over odds of SBOBET

Figure 10 : Fraction vs implied values for final over odds of SBOBET

The bookmaker SBOBET can be claimed as less successful about predicting whether the match will finish as over than the previous 4 bookmakers. Moreover, after changing its odds (from starting odd to final odd), its predictions become better. However, this improvement is again less sufficient than the previous 4 bookmakers. Therefore, it can be said that SBOBET is not a successful bookmaker compared to previous 4 bookmakers.

2.2.) Task 1.b

In this task, the same data was used for analyzing the performance of the bookmaker. The bookmaker Pinnacle was selected as the test bookmaker to analyze the accuracy of its over odds. Its implied probabilities was divided into bins and its performance for each bin was observed along years. The plots were drawn for each bin. However, in some cases there was not enough data to examine the performance of bookmaker. Therefore, some bins were combined and the recommendations were made based on combined data. It is expected to see that the fractions are in the corresponding bin for a good bookmaker.

Figure 11 : Fraction (empirical) vs implied probability (probabilistic) for Pinnacle for corresponding bin.

Since the data ( total number of matches ) for corresponding bin shown in Figure 11 is too small, the variation between fraction and implied probability is large. Therefore it cannot be meaningful to consider this bin for determining the accuracy of the bookmaker Pinnacle.

Figure 12 : Fraction (empirical) vs implied probability (probabilistic) for Pinnacle for corresponding bin.

For the corresponding ( (0.4-0.45] ), Pinnacle is good at determining odds for year 2012, 2013, 2014, 2015 and 2017. However, its odds for this bin in 2016 and 2018 can be accepted as not successful because the their implied probabilities are far away from the fraction in these years.

Figure 13 : Fraction (empirical) vs implied probability (probabilistic) for Pinnacle for corresponding bin.

For this bin, Pinnacle seems inefficient for determining odds in 2013 and 2017 compared to remaining years. We expect the fraction and implied probabilities to be closer to each other, however there are some variations between them.

Figure 14 : Fraction (empirical) vs implied probability (probabilistic) for Pinnacle for corresponding bin.

Since the data is comparatively small, there are obvious difference between implied probability and fraction in 2011, 2017 and 2018. It can be said that Pinnacle determines their odds accurately in the remaining years since the fractions are in the corresponding bin (.5,0.55].

Figure 15 : Fraction (empirical) vs implied probability (probabilistic) for Pinnacle for corresponding bin.

There is again huge variation between implied probability and fraction because off the small size of data. However, Pinnacle seems to be accurate for determining odds ( or probability for over ) in 2011,2015 and 2018.

Figure 16 : Fraction (empirical) vs implied probability (probabilistic) for Pinnacle for corresponding bin.

In years 2013, 2014, 2015, 2016 and 2017, 2018 the values of fraction are not meaningful since the data for corresponding bin is too small. However, in years 2011 and 2012, Pinnacle is good at determining over odds.

Since the last two graphs are not useful for evaluating the performance of bookmaker, it is reasonable to combine these two bins. In other words, the new bin is (0.55,0.65]. Then the new plot will be;

Figure 17 : Fraction (empirical) vs implied probability (probabilistic) for Pinnacle for corresponding bin.

In this graph, it can be seen that the prediction of Pinnacle for the bin (0.55,0.65] is quite accurate in 2011, 2014, 2015, 2016 and 2018 since the fractions are between the boundaries of corresponding bin ( (0.55,0.65] ). In the remaining years, there are some variations; however, in general, its performance can be accepted as good. Moreover, evaluation from this graph is more sensible to comment according to this graph since the data is larger

3.) Task 2

In this task, odd change in percentage between initial and final odds were analyzed for the performance of bookmaker, and visualizations were suggested. First of all, 10Bet was selected as test bookmaker to analyze its performance on changing odds. In this task, odds for homewin was the case and the data manipulation was carried out according to the change in homewin odds. Match results was obtained from the data and a column was created as Result_Home which takes the value of 1 if the match result is 1 (homewin), -1 otherwise. Then the Odd_change_percent column was created which shows the percentage of odd change for home win, and these values were divided into bins. In other words, it is the difference between starting and final odds in percentage. Then Bookmaker_prediction column was also created which has value of 1 if the bookmakers prediction is true, 0 otherwise. At this point, bookmakers prediction is based on its changes on odds. For example, if it decreases the odd of homewin, this means that the bookmaker thinks that home team will probably win the game. If the home team will win the match, the prediction of bookmaker is true, or vice versa.

After arranging the data, probability of the correctness of the bookmakers decision for each bin was plotted and the graph in figure 17 was obtained. On this graph, total number of games were also printed for each bin so that it can be easier to evaluate the performance of bookmaker.

Figure 18: Probability of correctness of the bookmakers decision for each bin

After evaluating the graph, it can be said that if odd change ( in percentage ) is between (-0.3-0], bookmakers prediction comparably false since their probabilities seems to less than 1. On the other hand, if the odd change in percentage is between (0-0.3], it can be said that the bookmakers decision is true because the probability for these bins are close to 0.6 ( greater than 0.5). There are some points which are strictly outliers because the match numbers are too small (for example, for the bin (1.2-1.3] there are only 3 matches, at the right corner on the graph). Therefore, they can be ignored. As a result, according to this visualization, anybody can have a guess whether a match result will be homewin or not by examining this graph. This visualization can be extended by considering awaywin or draw odds separately.

#Task 2
odds_1x2=odds[betType=='1x2' & bookmaker=='10Bet']
odds_1x2_initial=odds_1x2[,list(start_odd=odd[1]),
                          by=list(matchId,oddtype,bookmaker)]
odds_1x2_final=odds_1x2[,list(final_odd=odd[.N]),
                        by=list(matchId,oddtype,bookmaker)]
odds_1x2_total<-merge(odds_1x2_initial,odds_1x2_final,by=.EACHI)
odds_1x2_total<-merge(odds_1x2_total,matches,by="matchId")
odds_1x2_total[,IsOver:=NULL]
odds_1x2_total[,IsOverAlt:=NULL]
odds_1x2_total[,Result:="0"]
odds_1x2_total[HomeGoals-AwayGoals>0,Result:="1"] # We are focused on only homewin. Its numeric value is 1, otherwise result will take -1
odds_1x2_total[HomeGoals-AwayGoals<0,Result:="2"]
odds_1x2_total[,Odd_change_percent:=round((final_odd-start_odd)/start_odd,digits=2)] #Defining Odd_change_percent as the percentage of increment on odds for homewin
odds_1x2_total[,Result_Home:=-1]
odds_1x2_total[HomeGoals-AwayGoals>0,Result_Home:=1] #Result_Home=1 if result is one, -1 otherwise
odds_1x2_total[,Bookmaker_prediction:=0]
odds_1x2_total[Odd_change_percent*Result_Home<0,Bookmaker_prediction:=1] #+1 is true, while 0 represents false

cutpoints=seq(-0.5,1.3,0.1)
odds_1x2_total[,odds_cut_1x2:=cut(Odd_change_percent,cutpoints)]
#odds_1x2_total[,odds_cut_1x2:=NULL]
x<-mean(odds_1x2_total[odds_cut_1x2=="(-0.5,-0.4]",Bookmaker_prediction])

a<-odds_1x2_total[, .(count = .N, var = sum(Bookmaker_prediction)), by = odds_cut_1x2]
a[,mean:=var/count]
plot(a$odds_cut_1x2,a$mean,xlab="Change Percentage in Odds",ylab="Probability of Bookmaker's Decision is True",main="10Bet")
text(a$odds_cut_1x2,a$mean, labels=a$count, cex= 0.6, pos=1)
abline(0.5,0,col='red')
